title: For Sale:  Star Firestar M40 .40 S&W Pistol
location: Grey Forest (NW of SA), San Antonio, Texas
postcontent:
For sale is this Star Firestar M40 .40 S&W Pistol, made by Star (Spanish) and imported by Interarms. The only markings on it are "FIRESTAR" on the right side of the slide toward the muzzle; "STAR EIBAR SPAIN" and the Star logo on the left side of the frame near the muzzle; "INTERARMS ALEXANDRIA VIRGINIA" on the left side of the receiver near the muzzle; "CAL. .40 S&W" on the chamber end of the barrel, visible through the ejection port; and the serial number 2108XXX on the right-rear of the receiver. Although it is not so-marked, this is a model M40 pistol.

It's about 6-1/2" long, 4-5/8" high (+1/8" with 6-round magazine or +1/2" with 7-round magazine), about 1-1/4" wide and about 29.5 oz unloaded, 34.7 oz loaded with six 180-gn .40 rounds. Barrel length is about 3.3". The weapon is all steel with black rubber grips. All contact surfaces are checkered â€“ grip including front and rear surfaces, recurve of the trigger guard, hammer, slide release, magazine release, safety, and both sides of the slide â€“ except the trigger, which is smooth. The finish is in good shape, obviously not new, but clearly not abused. The barrel is in good shape, in fact you can see the rifling quite prominently in one of the pictures. Front sight is a blade adjustable for windage, looks like it had a dot in it once but not now, just an indentation. Rear sight with two white dots, adjustable for windage at least. Single action only, with a fairly light, crisp trigger.

Sale includes four magazines as shown â€“ two 6-rounders and two extended 7-rounders. The extended magazines do increase the overall size of the gun, but also improve the grip size. Also with the gun is an adjustable Uncle Mike's Sidekick holster, which can be used either left-or right-handed, inside the waist or outside. The holster includes a pocket for an additional magazine. It feels compact and solid and I think it would be a good choice for concealed carry.

The 9mm and .45ACP models of this pistol are far more common, in fact I could find no comparable sales of the M40 in this finish. Based on the completed sales records I could find of other Star pistols, I will offer this pistol with the four magazines and holster at $350.

title: For Sale:  ww2 1944 beretta m35
postcontent:
according to Whittington's records it was included in a delivery of 65,000 Beretta M1934/35 pistols delivered to the German Army Headquarters in Italy between Aug 1944 and Feb, 1945. Those serial # were 534000/599000.- "mine has #'s in that range"
After the 8 September 1943 armistice between Italy and the Allies, the Germans saddled Beretta with three engineers from Germany. Moreover the factory was garrisoned by the SS... Weapons of that time, even the ones produced for the Germans, bore the punch mark 4UT
(Quarto Ufficio tecnico di Controllo Armi e Munizioni--4th Technnical Control Unit
  an C. Still, in Axis Pistols, page 107, states,
"It is likely that almost all of the 4/UT, ...were used by the German Army". He also includes two other variations in this statement, "1944 dated and blank slide Model 1935".
  Ugo Menchini, in Pietro Beretta Le Automatiche, regarding an M1934, page 255, states,
"In late 1940 there appears an oval including the punch mark IVU. It refers to the 4th technical Control Unit of the FAG, where inspection was carried out."
 Note that, while they seem to represent the same inspectors, the "IVU" is not 
the same mark as the "4UT". The IVU would be found on the pre RSI model M1934, and the 4UT would be found on the RSI model M1935.
These are the reasons why I believe that it is likely that all of the 4UT Berettas were RSI pistols. 
great bore, crisp action no rust at all on the inside parts,minor rust pitting on one side of slide, half cock feature, perfect grips, lanyard.
great piece of history and a fun shooter.
3 0 3  4 3 0  8 1 9 2                $450 obo
very heavy overbuilt wartime piece.  REDACTED

title: For Sale:  Ortgies Vest Pocket Pistol .32 ACP
postcontent:
Designed by Heinrich Ortgies during WWI, these pistols were well-balanced, finely crafted, sturdy weapons much favored by competitive shooters. In 1921, prize winners at some 70% of principal shooting competitions had chosen Ortgies 7.65 mm pistols. An Ortgies was also carried by outlaw John Dillinger. 

Ortgies were also made in .32 ACP and .380 ACP. The .25 ACP is the smallest model. 

The pistol we are offering here is a late production model, .32 ACP, serial number 126xxx, built in Erfurt Germany probably not long before production stopped in 1924. Note the stylized cat's tail curving over its back for the D of Deutsche Werke 


Some surface rust but otherwise in good shape.

title: For Sale/Trade:  2 Rifles *REDUCED*
postcontent:
I have two rifles previously listed separate on Armslist- haven't had a whole lot of interest in them, so I thought I'd offer them together for trade.

First is an Hakim rifle in 8mm. This is basically a Swedish Ljungman rifle made for egypt. It is magazine fed, semi-auto, uses a direct impingement system similar to AR's, and has an excellent muzzle break to help with recoil. Very accurate with irons.

Second is an FR-8 in .308:
These are Spanish made bolt action carbines constructed from 8mm Mauser actions for .308. They were a stop gap measure before the CETME could be introduced. They are very short, and make excellent brush guns. Has a NATO flash hider and a fake gas tube up front to store a cleaning kit.
I've put 20 rounds through it since I've had it and it seems to be very accurate with open sights for within 100 yards. I haven't tried the adjustable peep sights which range out farther.

I have a little over 100 rounds of 8mm to go with the Hakim and a 3 boxes of ammo to go with the FR-8.

I's like to see these gone; they're taking up too much room in my cabinet, and I have no use for either one. I'm going for a trade value of $700. The Hakim's generally go for about 500 and the FR-8's for about 350 or more.
Would take cash for both or partial or whole trades. Ammo as well.
More pics and info upon request.
